    The purposes of this work were: \textbf{i)} to compare two farming
    systems (organic and conventional management on site since twenty
    five years) through the assessement of three soil's physical
    properties such as: bulk density, pore size distribution and
    aggregate stability; \textbf{ii)} to compare the effects of three
    tillage systems: plowing, chisel plowing and disk harrowing. The
    study is implemented within the \emph{MOLTE} project, a long term
    experiment of the University of Florence where, since 1991, at
    Montepaldi farm, located in San Casciano val di Pesa (FI) was
    carried out an experimentation on organic farming systems.
    The result of the analysis of the bulk density, show
    statistically significant differences between two farming systems,
    however these difference were so small that are negligible from a
    practical point of view. On the contrary the results of the pore size distribution 
    do not display statistically significant differences. 
    The aggregate stability shows that the aggregates from the conventional 
    soil are more stable than those from the organic one. 
  \end{engabstract}%
